menu "breadboard: bb_update_check"

config BB_UPDATE_CHECK_AUTOREGISTER
    bool "Auto-register GET /api/update/status via bb_registry"
    depends on !BB_OTA_STRATEGY_BOOT
    default y
    help
        When enabled, bb_update_check registers GET /api/update/status
        automatically via the bb_registry regular tier after the HTTP server
        starts. The polling timer is created at the same time but does not
        fire until bb_update_check_set_releases_url has been called.

        ENFORCE (B1-config-coupling): not selectable when BB_OTA_STRATEGY_BOOT
        is chosen (depends on !BB_OTA_STRATEGY_BOOT). Boot-mode boards run the
        manifest check synchronously at full early-boot heap inside the
        boot-mode worker; the recurring runtime task (~8 KB worker + HTTPS
        timer) is dead weight and cannot complete a TLS handshake on
        heap-tight boards. If a boot-mode board genuinely needs the runtime
        status route, switch the strategy to BB_OTA_STRATEGY_PULL.

config BB_UPDATE_CHECK_INTERVAL_S
    int "Default polling interval (seconds)"
    default 21600
    range 60 604800
    help
        Default poll interval when cfg.interval_s is 0. 21600 = 6 hours,
        which stays well under GitHub's 60 req/h unauthenticated rate
        limit even with many devices behind one NAT. Each tick the ESP-IDF
        worker picks the next interval as this value plus uniform ±10 min
        jitter (±600 s, floored at 60 s) to desynchronize fleets that
        reboot together.

config BB_UPDATE_CHECK_AUTO_ATTACH
    bool "Auto-attach update.available to /api/events"
    default y
    depends on BB_EVENT_ROUTES_AUTOREGISTER
    help
        When enabled, bb_update_check's init attaches "update.available"
        to the bb_event_routes SSE stream so /api/events surfaces it
        without an explicit consumer call. Disable if a consumer wants
        the bb_event topic for internal logic only.

config BB_UPDATE_CHECK_CUSTOM_PARSER_BUF_BYTES
    int "Custom parser response buffer size (bytes)"
    default 8192
    range 1024 65536
    help
        Size of the heap buffer allocated per fetch when a custom parser
        is registered via bb_update_check_set_parser(). The default GitHub
        parser is fully streaming and does not use this buffer. Custom
        parsers receive the complete response body here; if the response
        exceeds this limit, it is truncated and a warning is logged.
        Default 8192 saves 8 KB heap vs the old hardcoded 16384.
        Raise if your custom parser needs to process larger responses.

config BB_UPDATE_CHECK_JITTER_S
    int "Per-tick jitter half-range applied to the poll interval (seconds)"
    default 600
    range 0 3600
    help
        Each timer reschedule adds a uniform random offset in the range
        [-JITTER_S, +JITTER_S] to the base interval, floored at
        BB_UPDATE_CHECK_FLOOR_S. Setting to 0 disables jitter (every
        device fires at a fixed interval). Default 600 s (±10 minutes)
        matches the prior hardcoded value (no behavior change).

config BB_UPDATE_CHECK_FLOOR_S
    int "Minimum permitted poll interval after jitter application (seconds)"
    default 60
    range 10 300
    help
        Lower bound applied after the jitter offset is computed. Prevents
        the jitter from scheduling a check sooner than this many seconds.
        Default 60 matches the prior hardcoded value (no behavior change).

config BB_UPDATE_CHECK_TASK_CORE
    int "CPU core affinity for the on-demand update-check worker task"
    default 1
    range 0 1
    help
        Core on which the short-lived update-check worker task is pinned.
        Core 0 carries lwip/wifi/httpd; the mbedTLS handshake (200-600 ms)
        would starve IDLE0 on that core. Default 1 matches the prior
        hardcoded value (no behavior change). Set to tskNO_AFFINITY (-1)
        via bb_update_check_set_task_core() at runtime for no pinning.

config BB_UPDATE_CHECK_TASK_PRIORITY
    int "FreeRTOS priority for the on-demand update-check worker task"
    default 1
    range 1 24
    help
        FreeRTOS priority for the short-lived on-demand worker task that
        runs bb_update_check_run_one(). On boards running a CPU-bound task
        at a high priority (e.g. mining at priority 20), raise this above
        that task to avoid starvation during the mbedTLS handshake. Default
        1 (lowest app priority) matches the prior hardcoded value (no
        behavior change). Override at runtime via
        bb_update_check_set_task_priority().

endmenu
